\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Id pattered his way around the bed, mewing quietly and pressing his face into Paul\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s ear to purr loudly.  The cat's cold nosed forced him into consciousness, a sharp contrast to the warm morning that felt somehow indimidating.  In the sleepfulness of the morning he had forgotten the promises he had made the night before, and now as they came trickling back he felt his stomach sink and a hot buzz begining in his head, an uncomfortable-ness that plauged his entire body with a manic itch caused him to sit up and catch his breath.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Seven hours, he told himself.  By three o\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 clock you\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 ll be home.  }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Paul threw the corner of the comforter and towel over the curtain rack, allowing just a slice of light to illuminate his open closet.  Everything he owned was plain and functional - sweats, tshirts, dilapadated jeans; nothing really suited for gardening.  Still he dug through the piles that had collected beneath the empty hangers, hoping that some abberation waited for him at the bottom.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab He stood back, and looked himself in the mirror.  He wondered if Peter would have the same messy, loose curls that he did if he let his hair grow out.  Paul wasn\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t a huge fan of the military-esque buzz that Peter kept, but he could see why he did it - several months without maintenance left his hair piled haphazaardly upon his head, falling leftward and into his face just a bit.  The plain grey shirt he had picked out had a giant diagonal crease down the front from sitting beneath the pile of clothes in his closet, but this was ok.  Paul looked himself in the eye and repeated:}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab You will never see these people again after today.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Paul had not known Rebekkah before two days ago - he had passed her in the hallways at school, sure, still he knew her only as a component of a whole, the way he knew the few hundred others that he shared classrooms with.  She was damn pretty.  In a natural way - her straight brown hair looked good when she did nothing to it, her eyes were alluring because they were always glossed in wonder and sanguity.  It was not the proper application of makeup but that glow that made her look completed; even in baggy sweats, even on off days.  Paul had noticed all this, from afar, but this was nothing new.  There were pretty girls everywhere, girls that were pretty for a variety of reasons.  The part that moved Paul, as he had explained it to Peter, had nothing to do with appearance.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 No one, ever?\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0  Peter had asked.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 Well, no.\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0  he\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 d replied, \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 But that doesn\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t really bother me.  I like being left alone.\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 So when she came up to you - that was the first time someone tried to talk to you, since . . .?\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 Since I can remember, I guess.  Everyone knows I don\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t talk to people.\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 Does Rebekkah know that?\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 She\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 d had to\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 ve.\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 Then why did she come talk to you?\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 I don\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t know why.\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0 }
