\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 Remember that time that I pointed to the bird on the fence?\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0   Jacob reminisced.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0  . . . Yes\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0  Paul replied, his eyes still transfixed upon Rebekkah as she moved towards them with sandwiches.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 I have a confession.  When you turned your head, I threw a carrot seed in with your radish seed.  Don\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t worry, I remember exactly where.\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Rebekkah handed a sandwich to Paul.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0  . . -\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 We shall see Paul!  I still think there is hope for a Raddarrot of some kind; a hybrid, if you will.\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Rebekkah smiled, and wrinkled her nose at what she percieved as two new friends sharing a moment over a PB&J.  Quietly she slinked away as not to disturb the deep, meaningful conversation the two were having.  Paul briefly considered strangling Jacob, but as he was not prone to outward expression he simply sat there, listening to him ramble on and on in between the loudest chewing he could achieve.  }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab The afternoon was hotter than the morning, and the strength the food gave Paul wore off quickly.  Jacob continued his one sided banter about gardening, nature, birds, and everything else that seemed to pass his eye line.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 Ok so get this,\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0  Jacob pushed some long strands of hair out of his eyes, that had come unglued from the rest of his head from sweat.  \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 So normally, plants and things, they grow everywhere.\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Jacob offered some time for this to sink in, while Paul attempted to finish off the packet of seeds.  Eleven left.  Almost three o\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 clock.  Two thirty is close enough, right?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 In a garden though, you pick and choose what you want to grow in it.  You don\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t just let things grow, you make things grow, because you prefer them.  You see what I mean?\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0   Jacob pointed his spade at the four corners of the garden.  \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 You block it off, you put what you want in there.  And for a while its empty.  I bet people drive by this garden and think \hich\f0 \lquote \loch\f0 Oh, what a waste of space.  No nature, no nothing.\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0   But they don\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t know, something better than wilderness is coming!  Something planned.  Something intentional.\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0   Jacob leaned back on his arms, taking in the blank canvas of earth that he sat upon.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Paul pushed a pile of dirt of over his last seed.  He crumpled the packet and stuffed it in his back pocket, walking away too quickly to hear what Jacob was saying.  He walked behind Rebekkah, out of her sight, dropping the spade on the table, out the front gate of the garden.  It was two forty five.}
