\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab When Paul entered his house, Peter was watching TV on the couch.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 Oh shit, did you need a ride?  You could have called -\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Paul said noting, walking straight towards his room.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 Wait, do you want to - tell me anything about -\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0 }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Paul\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s door slid firmly into place, then there was the sound of the lock pivoting, and then there was silence.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Paul lay in his bed with his blankets completely covering him.  There were no clocks in Paul\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s room, so it\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s hard to say for how long he lay there, motionless.  When he pushed them off of him the light from the window was gone and the streetlights had come on all down the street, off into the distance til they were just little floating orbs of pale yellow light.  The sight filled Paul with a sort of dim peace.  }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Now uncovered in his bed, in the all but dark bedroom, Paul began to write in his spiral notebook.  It was filled with scattered thoughts and feelings, lacked dates or time periods or cohesion of any sort.  That\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s because it was not written to be read, simply to expel.  }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab I think I have a garden.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Paul twisted a pencap around in his mouth.  }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab I think my garden is very empty.  Maybe I don\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t water it enough, or too much.  Maybe I never planted anything.  Maybe I can\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t.  Maybe I wasn\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t meant to be planted on.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Would you believe that at that very moment, Rebekkah was writing in a notebook as well?  Her\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s was a full blown diary, dates and organization and all that.  She bought notebooks in packs of threes, filled them cover to cover.  Unfortunately, I can\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t tell you what she's written, out of respect for her privacy.  You wouldn\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t understand it anyway, her thoughts are too intimate to understand - that intimacy is where the the very concept of a diary finds its origin. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Alright, I will tell you a little bit.  Tonight, Rebekkah has written }
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab I am not a princess}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Over and over again.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \tab Here\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s something you might not know about girls - inside their head, there is an imago dei of everything a lady should be.  And inside that, there is a real girl - scared because she does not fill it out at all; everywhere there is leftover space, allowing sobs to return days, years later.  It is hard for them to tell sometimes if they are crying over something that happened today, or many years ago.  Emotions are cyclical like that, which is why at about the thirteenth iteration of I am not a princess Rebekkah burst into tears.  Whether it was about something that happened that day, or something that happened a long time ago, Rebekkah was unsure.}
